The Smith & Wesson SW99 is a modern, polymer frame pistol that is nearly identical to the Walther P99. The SW99 features an internal striker, as opposed to the classical external hammer. It is chambered in .40 S&W. The pistol lacks a manual safety; instead a de-cocking button is placed on the top rear section of the slide, which when actuated, places the firearm into double-action mode. This mechanism differs with each variation of the action, which will be explained below. The SW99 features several safety features including a loaded chamber indicator on the right side of the slide, a protruding, red-painted cocking indicator, and a drop safety. As with the P99, the cocking indicator does not protrude from the slide of the QA variant unless the weapon is fired, as it is in a constant partially cocked state. The SW99 also features a fully supported chamber design, which leaves no portion of the chambered round exposed. Because of this there is less chance of injury to the shooter and/or destruction of the pistol, should the casing head rupture.

A hard black case, lock, small cleaning kit, and holster will come with it as seen in the picture.

postcontent:
For sale is a "like new" Springfield XDS 45 ACP. It comes with two standard five round magazines and one extended seven round magazine. It also comes with Springfield XDS gear in the form of a range holster and magazine holster that holds both 7 and 5 round magazines. A grip insert, lock, barrel brush for cleaning, yellow and red fiber optic front sight replacements, user manual, and original test fire brass are also included. All of this comes in the sleek and slick looking XDS hard plastic carrying case. 

If you are looking for a good conceal carry weapon this is a great buy. It can be used affectively as a primary or a backup. This gun works perfect, I am just looking to upgrade to a slightly more expensive weapon and need the extra money. It has only fired 150 rounds and still looks like new.

I will entertain offers below the asking price if they are reasonable. However, I will throw in a box of 45 ACP if you pay the asking price.

Since I am not a licensed dealer and cannot use the FBI instant background check system, the final transfer will need to go through an Federal Firearms Licensee (FFL). If you would like to inspect the weapon before purchase we can arrange to do so.

If you are in or near Oklahoma City I know of an FFL that will complete the transfer for $10. This cost is on top of the sale price but can be negotiated. If you are outside of Oklahoma I will not ship to states in which this weapon is illegal. If you have a question as to whether or not you are legally allowed to own this gun in your state just go to the following address and to your state link to see (http://www.atf.gov/publications/firearms/state-laws/31st-edition/index.html). If your state is legal to ship to I will need a copy of an FFL of your choosing to ship to.

Do to the fact I am unlicensed, and this is a handgun, there is only one shipping option. This is UPS Next Day Air. FedEx and USPS will not allow an unlicensed dealer to ship a handgun interstate. UPS states here that they will only ship handguns via Next Day Air and only to a FFL, manufacturer, or law enforcement officer (http://www.ups.com/content/us/en/resources/ship/packaging/guidelines/firearms.html). Therefore shipping price is based on location and will originate from Oklahoma City, OK. The package is 6 pounds and will be shipped in a box approximately 16" x 14" x 4". Please check the shipping price if you are out of state as this will greatly affect the price.

title: For Sale:  Tangodown's new grip for the SCAR
postcontent:
First on the list to go was the standard A2 grip. I considered the Magpul MIAD grip as I already had one on my 16s, but I didn't want to hassle modifying it or my new rifles grip tang. The TangoDown's new BG17 grip is claimed to fit without modification, and it does. it's slightly wider than the A2 grip or the earlier TD BattleGrip,and incorporates a grip tang at the top also. The TD grip comes with a stainless steel screw and Allen wrench for mounting on any AR15 type rifle. To mount the grip on a SCAR you will need to use the FN grip screw.

The A2 grip removes easily. 
The TD grip is a very tight fit and until tightened in place has a gap between the the grip and frame. The internal storage compartment has changed also. It now has one large cavity vs. the 2 smaller battery storage cavities of the previous version, and a black storage cover instead of green.
The new grip will accommodate an AR15 bolt as well. 
I really like the BG17 on the SCAR, it fits well and feels good in the hand. It's slightly bigger than the old version and fills the hand better. The down side is that it creates a longer reach to the magazine release, For shooters with average sized hands this shouldn't be a problem.

I'm no chemical engineer, but the polymer TangoDown uses feels much tougher and more durable than the material used by FN in the lower receiver. 
No Trades at this time.
Will ship to FFL Dealer and buyer pays $35.00 for shipping.

From a review in Accurateshooter.com by Danny Reever: 
One of my tests included a Snellen Eye Chart, just like the one at your optometrist office. Instead of it hanging on a wall, I placed the Snellen Chart at 500 meters along with some previously-shot paper Ground Hog targets. Conditions were hazy and humid with moderate mirage. My Nightforce 12-42x56mm Benchrest riflescope set at 42X could read line 6 on the chart and I could distinguish only a few of the 6mm bullet holes. My Pentax PF100-ED set at 60X (to match the Kowa’s maximum power) was better. With the Pentax I could read line 7 on the chart and see more of the bullet holes. With the Kowa set at 60X, I could read line 8 on the chart and see all of the bullet holes on the white parts of the targets.. FYI, line 8 on the Snellen Chart defines 20-20 vision at 20 feet. Reading that at 500 meters (1641 feet) is pretty impressive!

I've had this pistol forever in my safe. Back when Bill Clinton was passing anti-gun legislation I bought some new Beretta 92FS pistols, a couple of them in stainless (Inox in Italian). Going through my safe I came across this Beretta that was never used. I tried looking for another NIB Stainless Beretta 92FS made in Italy to see what they are selling for, and I haven't seen a single one in a month or so of looking. So, based on that, I'm going to assume they are reasonably rare. If you've never compared one of the Italian made Stainless 94FS pistols made back then to the US made, you won't believe the difference in build quality. They feel completely different with the Italian model making the US model feel like it was cast in a sand mold and never polished.

Included is the pistol, original warranty and manual, original 'oiled paper' in the original box along with the original 2 stainless 15 round magazines. The date of manufacture for this pistol is mid 1994. I have not racked the slide to try to clean any old oil off of this pistol.

I actually found another of these that I bought at the time that has the beautiful original hardwood grips and I honestly don't think the slide on it has even been racked except when I bought it. I'm not sure I want to sell it. I fell in love with it's beauty all over again.  This is a listing for the beautiful one with original Beretta factory wood grips.

Sale to an individual will require the individual to have a carry permit and proper ID. Any shipping MUST go through FFL dealer at buyer's expense. I'll stay on top of removing the ad if I sell it or change my mind on selling. So, basically, if you're seeing this ad, it's probably still for sale. I seriously doubt that I want to sell both of my unfired Italian made Stainless 1994 production 92FS pistols.  I will remove the listing of the one that did not sell if one sells.  I know it comes across wrong, but I really don't care if I sell either of these.  With the current political atmosphere, it seems highly likely high cap firearms will have some sort of ban placed on them.  This pistol and the other Beretta are examples of some of the highest quality high capacity 9mm pistols ever built in the world.  I'm not afraid of holding on to them if the economics are not right for them to sell right now.  Sorry, but I'm not interested in any trades at this time.

title: For Sale:  LNIB flat dark earth FN FNP 9 USG w/night sights, five 16 round mags
postcontent:
I have a LNIB FN FNP 9 USG with 2013 dated Ameriglo night sights (green dots, Trijicon marked front and rear) up for sale. 

My FN FNP 9 has a flat dark earth frame, and has only had 200 rounds through it since new. It is in like new condition. The only mark on it is on the right side of the front sight, where the sight pusher dinged it a little bit. I touched it up and it is hardly noticeable. It also comes with 5 factory 16 round magazines.

Price is $550 firm. 

Text or email me here if interested, or if you've got any questions. Thanks for looking.

These are older pics, before I installed the night sights. If you want more recent pics, I can do that for you.

My number is five4one-720-3873.
